  "prompt": "How do you play the game Snaps?",
  "response": "Snaps is a simple, fast-paced card game, perfect for kids and adults. Here's how to play:\n\n**What You Need:**\n\n*   A standard deck of 52 playing cards.\n\n**Players:**\n\n*   2 or more players (usually 2-6 is ideal).\n\n**Objective:**\n\n*   To be the first player to call \"Snaps\" when two cards of the same rank are played consecutively on the central pile.\n*   To collect all the cards.\n\n**Gameplay:**\n\n1.  **Deal:** The dealer shuffles the deck and deals all the cards face down to the players. It doesn't matter if some players have slightly more cards than others. Players keep their cards in a face-down stack in front of them.\n\n2.  **Starting the Play:** The player to the dealer's left starts.\n\n3.  **Placing Cards:** The starting player takes the top card from their pile and places it face up in the center of the table, announcing the rank of the card (e.g., \"Seven,\" \"Queen,\" \"Ace\").\n\n4.  **Taking Turns:** Play continues clockwise. Each player takes their top card and places it face up on top of the central pile, announcing the rank of the card.\n\n5.  **The \"Snaps\" Moment:** *This is the core of the game.* When two cards of the **same rank** are played consecutively on the central pile, the first player to shout \"Snaps!\" wins the pile.\n\n    *   **Example:** Player A plays a \"King.\" Player B plays a \"King\" on top of it. Any player can shout \"Snaps!\"\n    *   **Speed and Observation are Key:** Players need to be quick to spot matching ranks and call \"Snaps!\" before anyone else.\n\n6.  **Winning the Pile:** The player who correctly calls \"Snaps!\" takes the entire pile of face-up cards and adds them to the bottom of their own face-down pile.\n\n7.  **False Snaps:** If a player calls \"Snaps!\" incorrectly (i.e., the two cards are *not* of the same rank), they must give one card from the bottom of their pile to each of the other players.  If they have no cards to give, they are out of the game.  (This is a common rule variant \u2013 see 'Variations' below for alternatives).\n\n8.  **Continuing Play:** Play continues with the next player after the one who won the last \"Snaps!\" pile. They start a new central pile.\n\n**Winning the Game:**\n\n*   The game continues until only one player has all the cards. That player is the winner.\n*   Alternatively, you can play for a set amount of time and count the number of cards each player has at the end. The player with the most cards wins.\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n*   **Focus on the Rank:** Pay attention *only* to the rank of the cards (Ace, 2, 3, ... 10, Jack, Queen, King). Suits (hearts, diamonds, clubs, spades) are irrelevant.\n*   **Speed is Essential:** Be quick to notice matching cards and shout \"Snaps!\" before anyone else.\n*   **Don't Jump the Gun:** Make sure you're certain the cards match before shouting \"Snaps!\" to avoid the penalty.\n*   **Enunciation:** Clearly state the rank of each card as you play it. This helps everyone track the game.\n\n**Variations:**\n\n*   **Penalty for False Snaps:** Instead of giving a card to each player, a false \"Snaps\" caller might have to place one or more of their cards at the bottom of the pile or be temporarily excluded from calling \"Snaps\".  Or they might simply skip their next turn.  Choose a penalty that works well for your group.\n*   **Multiple Decks:** For larger groups, you can use two or more decks of cards.\n*   **Sound Snaps:** Another variation involves calling \u201cSnaps\u201d based on a sound or word being spoken. For example, instead of matching ranks, you could call \u201cSnaps\u201d whenever the word \u201cthe\u201d is spoken in conversation.\n*   **Specific Rank Snaps:** Only call snaps on a specific rank, for example only call snaps when there are two Aces in a row.\n\n**Tips for Winning:**\n\n*   **Concentrate:** Pay close attention to the cards being played.\n*   **Be Quick:** Practice your reflexes to call \"Snaps!\" quickly.\n*   **Don't Get Distracted:** Avoid side conversations that might cause you to miss a \"Snaps\" opportunity.\n*   **Anticipate:** Try to anticipate what cards are likely to be played next.\n\nSnaps is a fun and easy game that can be enjoyed by people of all ages. Enjoy!\n",
